Worried by the spread of the coronavirus in the Federal Capital Territory (FCT), the Federal Capital Territory Administration (FCTA) has restricted business and commercial activities in the territory to 15 hours daily. FCT minister, Malam Muhammad Musa Bello, who announced the restriction while addressing journalists in Abuja yesterday, explained that from today, businesses and commercial activities in the territory must be restricted from 9pm to 6am, so as to avoid unnecessary movements. Bello announced the constitution of five monitoring committees to ensure the enforcement of rules and regulations on the restriction order in the territory. According to him one of teams will check and monitor parks, event centres, night clubs, restaurants and the markets, while another team will monitor motor parks, bus terminals, even as the third team would monitor compliance in places of worship, just as the fourth team would monitor compliance in educational institutions. The minister added that all the teams would also be constituted by the respective six area councils chairmen in the FCT, adding that the whole idea is to ensure that residents comply with the regulations against the spread of the coronavirus.  He announced that eating in restaurants in the territory is discouraged, unless within established hotels, where the principle of social distancing would be strictly adopted, just as he advised restaurant operators to provide services only in manner that would allow for take away.  